+{"type":"message","id":"11e397d6","parentId":"409ae86a","timestamp":"2026-03-24T15:42:10.194Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Operator notes for this run:\n## Operator note — 2026-03-24T14:22:02.774Z\n\nThis step is BACKEND ONLY. Do NOT touch any frontend files. Work exclusively in backend/src/. You must: (1) Create Flyway migration V3__add_ticket_priority.sql, (2) Add TicketPriority\n │ enum, PagedTicketResponse, TicketDetailResponse, TicketSummaryResponse, LinkedCommitEntry, CreateTicketFromCommitRequest records, (3) Add paginated/filterable ticket list endpoint, (4)\n │ Add /api/tickets/summaries endpoint, (5) Add /api/tickets/from-commit endpoint, (6) Add /api/users/{userId}/plan-history endpoint, (7) Add /api/teams/{teamId}/history endpoint, (8) Add\n │ /api/commits/{commitId}/carry-forward-lineage alias. All work in Java backend only. The frontend files already exist and should NOT be modified in this step\n\nThese notes are authoritative user steering for this run. Follow them unless they directly conflict with the repository state or the controller's explicit task.\n\nPlan overview:\n{\n  \"goal\": \"Build the Weekly Commit Module v1 — a production micro-frontend (TypeScript/React) with Java 21 modular-monolith backend replacing 15Five for weekly planning. Implements structured weekly commitments with RCDO strategy linkage, chess-layer prioritization, lock/reconcile lifecycle with immutable snapshots, explicit carry-forward with provenance, native tickets with status workflow, manager team dashboard with exception review, conservative explainable AI assistance, rules-based notifications, derived read models for reporting, and comprehensive audit logging. Delivered as a route-level Module Federation remote integrated into the PA host app. Note: The PRD recommends Java 21 (§22) and all checks are npm-based; the monorepo root package.json orchestrates both the TypeScript frontend (Vite/React) and Java backend (Gradle) via shell-out scripts. SQL migrations use Flyway against PostgreSQL.\",\n  \"totalSteps\": 20,\n  \"stepTitles\": [\n    \"1. Monorepo scaffolding and build infrastructure\",\n    \"2. Domain model types, enums, and database schema\",\n    \"3. RCDO hierarchy management API\",\n    \"4. Weekly plan creation and commit CRUD API\",\n    \"5. Lock lifecycle and baseline snapshot API\",\n    \"6. Post-lock scope change and reconciliation API\",\n    \"7. Carry-forward and ticket/work item API\",\n    \"8. Team weekly view, manager review, and permissions API\",\n    \"9. Frontend micro-frontend setup and routing\",\n    \"10. RCDO management UI\",\n    \"11. My Week page with commit list and capacity meter\",\n    \"12. Lock flow and reconcile view UI\",\n    \"13. Team Week dashboard UI\",\n    \"14. Backend ticket and supplementary API contract alignment\",\n    \"15. Frontend ticket contract alignment and Tickets UI completion\",\n    \"16. Notifications backend and frontend panel\",\n    \"17. AI provider abstraction, commit assistance, and risk detection\",\n    \"18. Derived read models and operational reporting\",\n    \"19. Configuration management and admin settings\",\n    \"20. Audit logging, accessibility, and integration polish\"\n  ]\n}\n\nPrevious step 16 (Notifications backend and frontend panel) has been completed and approved.\nFiles changed in the previous step:\n.pi/duet/runs/2026-03-24T03-49-04-151Z-dd75a832/cost.json\n.pi/duet/runs/2026-03-24T03-49-04-151Z-dd75a832/observations.jsonl\n.pi/duet/runs/2026-03-24T03-49-04-151Z-dd75a832/sessions/continuous/relay-a/2026-03-24T04-23-35-130Z_4c4202d2-9023-459a-b908-dfaede19919d.jsonl\n.pi/duet/runs/2026-03-24T03-49-04-151Z-dd75a832/sessions/continuous/relay-b/2026-03-24T04-35-30-972Z_471484d6-96e0-4a6b-86fc-b9b081fa294f.jsonl\n.pi/duet/runs/2026-03-24T03-49-04-151Z-dd75a832/state.json\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/carryforward/service/CarryForwardService.java\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/domain/entity/Notification.java\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/domain/repository/NotificationDeliveryRepository.java\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/domain/repository/NotificationRepository.java\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/lock/service/LockService.java\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/reconcile/service/ReconciliationService.java\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/reconcile/service/ScopeChangeService.java\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/ticket/service/TicketService.java\nbackend/src/test/java/com/weeklycommit/reconcile/service/ScopeChangeServiceTest.java\n.pi/duet/runs/2026-03-24T03-49-04-151Z-dd75a832/steps/16\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/domain/enums/NotificationEvent.java\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/notification\nbackend/src/main/resources/db/migration/V4__add_notification_priority.sql\nbackend/src/test/java/com/weeklycommit/notification\n\nYour session has context from prior steps. The repository may have changed since your last turn.\nBefore making assumptions about file contents, verify the current state of any files you need to modify.\nDo NOT re-read files that are unrelated to the current step.\n\nStep 17: AI provider abstraction, commit assistance, and risk detection\n{\n  \"id\": \"step-17\",\n  \"title\": \"AI provider abstraction, commit assistance, and risk detection\",\n  \"description\": \"Implement the AI foundation, commit-level assistance (PRD §17 capabilities 1-3), and risk/reconciliation assistance (capabilities 4-6). These are merged into one step because they share the provider abstraction, suggestion storage, and feedback infrastructure.\\n\\n**AI provider abstraction (backend):**\\n- `AiProvider` interface: `generateSuggestion(context: AiContext): AiSuggestionResult`. Context includes commit data, plan data, RCDO tree, historical patterns.\\n- `AiProviderRegistry`: registers providers, selects active provider. Supports disabling AI entirely via feature flag.\\n- Graceful degradation: if provider unavailable or disabled, all AI endpoints return empty suggestions with `aiAvailable: false` flag. Core workflow unaffected.\\n- Default implementation: stub provider for development; production provider pluggable.\\n\\n**AI suggestion and feedback storage:**\\n- `AiSuggestion` records: id, userId, suggestionType, context hash, suggestion payload, rationale text, modelVersion, createdAt.\\n- `AiFeedback` records: suggestionId, action (ACCEPTED, DISMISSED, EDITED), timestamp.\\n- Every suggestion stores rationale explaining why it was generated.\\n\\n**Commit drafting assistance (capability 1):**\\n- `POST /api/ai/commit-draft-assist`: returns suggestions for improved title, description, success criteria, estimate based on similar past commits. Suggestions are editable proposals, never auto-applied.\\n- Frontend: 'AI Assist' button on CommitForm. Shows suggestion panel with accept/edit/dismiss per suggestion.\\n\\n**Commit quality linting (capability 2):**\\n- `POST /api/ai/commit-lint`: returns lint results. Checks: vague titles, missing success criteria for King/Queen, parent-level RCDO when leaf exists, duplicate/near-duplicate titles, estimate inconsistency, over-fragmented plan.\\n- Results separated into `hardValidation` (blocks lock) and `softGuidance` (informational only).\\n- Frontend: AI Lint Panel on My Week page.\\n\\n**RCDO link suggestions (capability 3):**\\n- `POST /api/ai/rcdo-suggest`: suggests primary RCDO with confidence score and rationale. Only surface above threshold (default 0.7). Never auto-link.\\n- Frontend: suggestion with accept/dismiss in RCDO selector.\\n\\n**Risk detection (capability 4):**\\n- `RiskDetectionService`: computes risk signals per plan on lock and daily for LOCKED plans.\\n- v1 signals with rationale: overcommit, undercommit, repeated carry-forward (streak >= 2), blocked critical (King/Queen + BLOCKED ticket > 2 days), scope volatility (> 3 changes).\\n- Stored in `ai_suggestion` table with type RISK_SIGNAL.\\n- `GET /api/plans/{id}/risk-signals`. Frontend: risk flag icons on commits/plans with rationale tooltips. Hidden from peers.\\n\\n**Reconciliation assistance (capability 5):**\\n- `POST /api/ai/reconcile-assist`: likely outcomes for unlinked commits, draft summary of changes, carry-forward recommendations.\\n- Frontend: 'AI Assist' panel on ReconcilePage.\\n\\n**Manager summary (capability 6):**\\n- `GET /api/teams/{id}/week/{weekStart}/ai-summary`: team summary citing top RCDO branches, unresolved exceptions, carry-forward patterns, critical blocked items. Must cite underlying objects.\\n- Frontend: summary card at top of Team Week dashboard.\\n\\n**Unit tests:** provider graceful degradation, suggestion storage/retrieval, feedback recording, draft assistance structured suggestions, lint hard vs soft, RCDO confidence threshold, each risk signal type with rationale, daily risk job, reconcile assistance, manager summary cites sources, privacy (hidden from peers), AI down returns empty without error.\",\n  \"requiredChecks\": [\n    \"lint\",\n    \"typecheck\",\n    \"unit\",\n    \"build\"\n  ]\n}\n\nYou are the first agent to work on this step.\nImplement the changes described above, run checks to verify, and fix any issues before handing off.\nBe thorough — the next agent will review your work and should find it correct.\n\nPrior observations from earlier steps (address if they fall within this step's scope):\n- [MEDIUM] step 1 backend/build.gradle.kts: Uses Eclipse JDT formatter instead of google-java-format because google-java-format (and palantirJavaFormat) rely on `com.sun.tools.javac.util.Log$DeferredDiagnosticHandler.getDiagnostics()` which was removed in JDK 25. Future steps should be aware of this constraint; a switch to google-java-format would require either downgrading the JDK to ≤24 or waiting for a google-java-format release that supports JDK 25.\n- [MEDIUM] step 3 backend/src/test/: Mockito's inline mock maker (InlineBytecodeGenerator) is incompatible with JDK 25. Switched to subclass mock maker via the extensions file. This means final classes/methods cannot be mocked in tests — not an issue for our service classes but worth noting for future steps.\n- [MEDIUM] step 3 backend/src/test/resources/mockito-extensions/org.mockito.plugins.MockMaker: Set to `mock-maker-subclass` to work around Mockito inline-mock-maker incompatibility with JDK 25. This means final classes/methods cannot be mocked in tests. Not an issue today, but future steps adding mocks of final types will need to handle this.\n- [MEDIUM] step 5 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/lock/service/LockService.java: Auto-lock idempotency is implemented for repeat calls, but the step also called for optimistic locking or compare-and-swap to protect concurrent runners. I did not see explicit concurrency protection beyond state checks.\n- [MEDIUM] step 5 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/lock/service/LockService.java: Auto-lock idempotency relies only on a state check (DRAFT guard). There is no database-level optimistic lock (`@Version`) to protect against concurrent auto-lock runners. This is acceptable for v1 given single-instance deployment, but a future step should add `@Version` to `WeeklyPlan` and a Flyway migration for the `version` column if concurrent scheduling ever becomes a concern.\n- [MEDIUM] step 6 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/reconcile/service/ReconciliationService.java: The `getReconciliationView` method allows state RECONCILING or RECONCILED, but `setCommitOutcome` only allows RECONCILING. If a manager views a RECONCILED plan via `getReconciliationView`, then tries to `setCommitOutcome`, they get a 400. This is correct behavior but worth documenting clearly in the API.\n- [MEDIUM] step 6 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/reconcile/service/ScopeChangeService.java: The `removePostLockCommit` method sets `outcome = CANCELED` immediately (pre-reconciliation). During `submitReconciliation`, this commit is treated as already having an outcome (CANCELED), which is correct. However, calling `setCommitOutcome` on an already-CANCELED (removed) commit during RECONCILING would allow overriding the post-lock cancellation — a guard could prevent this in a future step.\n- [MEDIUM] step 8 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/team/service/TeamWeeklyViewService.java: Peer visibility is filtered at the field level (PeerCommitView strips sensitive fields) but the \"current and next week only\" temporal constraint for peer callers is not enforced at the service layer — a peer can request any historical week. Not a breaking issue for v1 but worth tightening in a future step.\n- [MEDIUM] step 8 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/team/service/TeamWeeklyViewService.java: `checkCanAccessTeam` requires the caller to be a team member. An ADMIN-managed parent team manager without explicit membership in a child team would be blocked from viewing that child team's data. This is consistent with current behavior but the \"indirect reports' aggregates\" capability from the step spec is not fully exercised in the team-week endpoint.\n- [MEDIUM] step 8 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/team/service/TeamWeeklyViewService.java: Peer visibility appears field-filtered, but the “current and next week only” peer time-window rule may not be enforced server-side for arbitrary requested weeks.\n- [MEDIUM] step 12 frontend/src/routes/MyWeek.tsx: The pre-lock validation panel derives soft warnings client-side from commit data, but the actual hard-error list only appears AFTER the lock attempt returns validation errors. This means the user sees the panel before errors are shown. A dedicated `GET /api/plans/{id}/validate` endpoint could provide server-side validation without actually locking, giving immediate feedback. This is a future enhancement.\n- [MEDIUM] step 13 frontend/src/components/teamweek/ByRcdoSection.tsx: The ByRcdoSection only shows `totalPoints` (planned) per RCDO node since the backend's `RcdoRollupEntry` doesn't include achieved points. A future enhancement could add achieved point rollup to the backend DTO.\n- [MEDIUM] step 13 frontend/src/routes/TeamWeek.tsx: The step calls for a manager team selector for users who can manage multiple teams, but the current host bridge only exposes `currentTeam` and the route param, not a selectable team list. The dashboard currently supports route-based team selection, but not an in-page selector.\n- [MEDIUM] step 13 frontend/src/routes/TeamWeek.tsx: ByPersonSection supports `onViewMemberPlan`, but TeamWeek does not wire a click-through action yet, so the “view full plan detail for a direct report” behavior is still not exposed from the page.\n- [MEDIUM] step 13 frontend/src/routes/TeamWeek.tsx: In-page team selector for managers with multiple teams is not implemented — only route-based selection via param. Step 13 spec calls for an explicit team selector widget.\n- [MEDIUM] step 13 frontend/src/routes/TeamWeek.tsx: ByPersonSection `onViewMemberPlan` prop is not wired to a click-through navigation action in TeamWeekPage, so the \"view full plan detail for a direct report\" behavior is not exposed.\n- [MEDIUM] step 14 frontend/src/routes/Tickets.tsx: The create-from-commit flow is accessible from MyWeek only (via CommitList). The Tickets page doesn't yet have a standalone \"create from commit\" action — the API endpoint `/api/tickets/from-commit` is defined but not directly used from the Tickets page. This is by design (the PRD says it's a commit action), but worth noting.\n- [MEDIUM] step 14 frontend/src/api/ticketApi.ts: `getPlanHistory`, `getCarryForwardLineage`, and `getTeamHistory` endpoints are defined in the frontend but have no corresponding backend controllers yet — they will return 404 until implemented in future steps.\n- [MEDIUM] step 15 frontend/src/api/ticketTypes.ts: The `TicketResponse` interface is named differently from the backend's `TicketDetailResponse`. While functionally equivalent, this naming in